{{Infobox U.S. Courts of Appeals case |Litigants=Edwards v. Habib |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] |CourtSeal= |ArgueDate=January 22, |ArgueYear=1968 |DecideDate=May 17, |DecideYear=1968 |FullName=Yvonne C. Edwards v. Nathan Habib |Citations=397 [[Federal Reporter|F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/397/687/359942/ 687] |Prior= |Subsequent=Petition for rehearing [[en banc]] denied, July 11, 1968 |Holding= |Judges=[[John A. Danaher]], [[James Skelly Wright]], [[Carl E. McGowan]] |Majority=Wright |JoinMajority=McGowan (Part III only) |Concurrence=McGowan |Dissent=Danaher |LawsApplied= }} '''''Edwards v. Habib''''', [[case citation|397]] [[Federal Reporter|F.2d]] 687 (D.C. Cir. 1968)<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Edwards v. Habib |vol=397 |reporter=F.2d |opinion=687 |pinpoint= |court=D.C. Cir. |date=1968 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/397/687/359942/ |accessdate=2017-10-31 |quote=}}</ref>, was a [[legal case|case]] decided by the [[D.C. Circuit]] that includes the first recognition of [[retaliatory eviction]] as a defense to [[eviction]] in [[real property law|landlord-tenant law]].
==Factual background== Plaintiff Edwards [[lease|rented]] property from defendant Habib on a month-to-month basis. Habib failed to address sanitary code violations brought up by Edwards, so Edwards reported Habib to the Department of Licenses and the Inspection Department. An inspection revealed 40 sanitary code violations, and Habib was ordered to rectify the violations. After the inspection, Habib obtained a default judgment against Edwards in a statutory eviction action.
==Holding== The court held that a tenant cannot be evicted for reporting sanitary code violations, and this became known as the defense of retaliatory eviction.<ref>Casner, A.J. et al. ''Cases and Text on Property, Fifth Edition.'' Apsen Publishers, New York, NY: 2004. P. 150</ref>
