During the beginning of the German invasions during [[World War II]], [[Jacques Jaujard]], the director of the French [[Réunion des Musées Nationaux|Musées Nationaux]], foreshadowed the fall of France and decided to organize the evacuation of the [[Louvre]] art collection in province.<ref name="guardian">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/nov/22/mona-lisa-spirited-away-from-nazis-jacques-jaujard-louvre | title=Saviour of France’s art: how the Mona Lisa was spirited away from the Nazis | publisher=[[The Guardian]] | quote=''On 25 August 1939, Jaujard closed the Louvre for three days, officially for repair work. For three days and nights, hundreds of staff, art students and employees of the Grands Magasins du Louvre department store carefully placed treasures in white wooden cases.'' | date=2014-11-22 | accessdate=2018-01-13}}</ref>
== Evacuation of the art collection == [[File:Nike descending staircase 3sept1939.jpg|thumb|right|The Winged Victory of Samothrace was carefully lowered down a ramp]] [[File:La Grande Gallerie désertée.jpg|thumb|upright|right|The Grande Gallerie in September 1939]] On 25 August 1939, the Louvre was closed for 3 days, officially for repairs. However, many of the Louvre art collection was hauled on trucks (203 vehicles transporting 1862 wooden cases) and sent to [[Château de Chambord]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/arts-expositions/2013/11/13/03015-20131113ARTFIG00266-le-louvre-ou-l-art-de-resister.php | title=Le Louvre ou l'art de résister | publisher=[[Le Figaro]] | date=2013-11-13 | accessdate=2018-01-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://twistedsifter.com/2013/05/louvre-and-mona-lisa-world-war-2/ | title=How France Hid the Louvre’s Masterpieces During WWII | publisher=twistedsifter.com | date=2013-05-16 | accessdate=2018-01-13}}</ref> The crates had a marking to identify the importance of the art pieces they contained: a yellow circle for very valuable art pieces, green for major works and red for world treasures (the [[Mona Lisa]] was marked with three red circles).
Some of the art pieces were too big to be fit in a truck. For example [[The Raft of the Medusa]] had to be covered with a blanket. When the truck initially arrived at Versailles on his route to Chambord, the canvas touched an electric cable and created a short-circuit which switched off the electricity in the whole town. After that, the routes were carefully planned to avoid this type of problems, and attendants which poles were responsible to deal with electric or phone cables.<ref>{{Citation |title=Illustre et Inconnu. Comment Jacques Jaujard a sauvé le Louvre}}</ref><ref>Nicholas, Lynn H. (1994) ''[[The Rape of Europa (book)|The Rape of Europa: The Fate of Europe's Treasures in the Third Reich and the Second World War]]''. New York: [[Alfred A. Knopf]], pp. 54–55. {{ISBN|978-0-679-40069-1}}; OCLC 246524635</ref>
The last art piece to leave the museum was the [[Winged Victory of Samothrace]], which was moved on September 3, 1939, the day the French ultimatum to Germany expired.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lemonde.fr/televisions-radio/article/2014/10/31/exode-artistique_4516306_1655027.html | title=Exode artistique | publisher=[[Le Monde]] | date=2014-10-31 | accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref>
Throughout the war, the arts pieces were clandestinely moved from chateau to chateau to avoid being taken back by the Nazis.<ref name="guardian"/> For example, the ''Mona Lisa'' was moved from Chambord to several castles and abbeys, to finish at the end of the war at the [[Musée Ingres]] in [[Montauban]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2013/nov/12/nazis-steal-mona-lisa-louvre | title=Did the Nazis steal the Mona Lisa? | publisher=[[The Guardian]] | quote=''The only wartime documents available about the Mona Lisa say that on 27 August 1939 it was packed in a specially-marked crate, tailor-made in 1938, of double-thick poplar wood. Along with other artworks from French national museums, it was sent for storage, first to Chambord Castle in the Loire Valley. On 5 June 1940, it was transferred to Chauvigny on a cushioned stretcher in the back of an ambulance, which had been sealed to keep the humidity constant (the official who accompanied the painting arrived nearly asphyxiated from the lack of circulation in the sealed vehicle). In September, it moved again, to the Ingres Museum in Montauban, before a final move to Montal in 1942'' | date=2013-11-12 | accessdate=2018-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/84865/how-mona-lisa-escaped-destruction-during-world-war-ii | title=How the Mona Lisa Escaped Destruction During World War II | publisher=[[Mental Floss]] | date=2016-08-25 | accessdate=2018-07-15}}</ref>
== The arrival of the German army in Paris == On 16 August 1940, count [[Franz von Wolff-Metternich]], who was responsible of the conservation of the French art collections under the [[Kunstschutz]] principle, arrived in Paris to oversee France’s art collection, but the museum was almost empty. He knew what was going on but voluntarily did not do anything.<ref name="guardian"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k9647526h/f30.item.r=Jacques%20Jaujard | title=In Memoriam - Jacques Jaujard | publisher=gallica.bnf.fr | accessdate=2018-01-13}}</ref>
